---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
import Timestamp from '../components/Timestamp.astro';
import Label from '../components/Label.astro';

// Sample content — a plausible essay, so we can judge Newsreader at real length.
const constellations = ['conditions, not character', 'the invisible graveyard'];
---

<Base title="Forgiveness — It Only Happens Once">
  <main class="px-6 py-16 sm:py-24">
    <article class="prose-measure mx-auto">
      <!-- which constellations this piece lives in -->
      <div
        class="flex flex-wrap items-center gap-x-5 gap-y-1 font-serif text-sm text-base-content/45"
      >
        {
          constellations.map((l) => (
            <span class="inline-flex items-center gap-1.5">
              <span class="text-primary">✦</span>
              {l}
            </span>
          ))
        }
      </div>

      <h1 class="mt-6 font-display text-4xl leading-[1.1] font-light sm:text-6xl">
        Forgiveness
      </h1>

      <div class="mt-6 flex items-center gap-3 text-sm text-base-content/40">
        <Timestamp date="2023-05-31" />
        <span class="font-sans">·</span>
        <span class="font-sans">6 min read</span>
      </div>

      <div class="reading mt-14">
        <p class="reading-lead">
          For most of my life I believed forgiveness was a decision — a door
          you chose to open, a generosity you extended by force of will. I don't
          believe that anymore.
        </p>

        <p>
          What changed wasn't my heart. It was my model of people. Somewhere
          along the way I started tracing behavior back to its causes — really
          tracing it, past the point where blame is comfortable — and I kept
          arriving at the same place: <em>conditions</em>. The person who hurt
          me was, in almost every case, doing the only thing their history had
          equipped them to do. Not excused. Explained.
        </p>

        <p>
          And explanation, it turns out, does something that willpower never
          could. When you follow the full causal chain behind an action, the
          <em>agent</em> you wanted to blame quietly dissolves. There is no one
          standing at the center of it who could have done otherwise. What's
          left isn't anger. It's a kind of tired tenderness.
        </p>

        <blockquote>The best revenge is not to be like your enemy.</blockquote>

        <h2>What understanding does</h2>

        <p>
          I used to think this made me soft — that refusing to hold a grudge was
          a failure of self-respect. I've come to think the opposite.
          Resentment assumes a free agent who <strong>chose</strong> to wrong
          you. Remove the assumption and resentment has nothing to hold onto; it
          isn't suppressed, it's <em>unfounded</em>. That's not weakness. It's
          just accuracy.
        </p>

        <p>
          There is a cost to seeing this way, and I won't pretend there isn't.
          If no one is finally to blame, then some part of you has to carry the
          grief without the relief of having someone to hand it to. The pain was
          real. It simply didn't have an author.
        </p>

        <h2>The part I keep having to relearn</h2>

        <p>
          The strange thing is how hard it is to extend the same mercy inward. I
          can forgive almost anyone their conditions — except the younger
          version of myself, who by the exact same logic could not have done
          otherwise either. The framework that sets everyone else free keeps
          making an exception for me. I'm still
          <a href="#">working on that</a>.
        </p>

        <p>
          But that is the direction, at least. Forgiveness stopped being
          something I <em>do</em> and became something I <em>see</em> — and once
          you see it, you can't quite unsee it. It only happens once, this life,
          and most of the people in it are trying about as hard as their
          conditions allow.
        </p>
      </div>

      <!-- where it lives -->
      <footer class="mt-20 border-t border-base-300 pt-8">
        <Label variant="voice">This piece lives in</Label>
        <div class="mt-4 flex flex-wrap gap-x-8 gap-y-2 text-xl">
          {
            constellations.map((l) => (
              <a
                href="#"
                class="inline-flex items-center gap-2 font-light transition-colors hover:text-primary"
              >
                <span class="text-primary">✦</span>
                {l}
              </a>
            ))
          }
        </div>
      </footer>
    </article>
  </main>
</Base>
